entry.title: [CrOS Cellular] Allow users to modify APN for managed eSIMs.
entry.content:

Previously, users could not set the APN for managed eSIM profiles

would not be propagated to shill because CustomAPNList is not marked

as a recommended field.

entry.title: Add --wrap-static-fns support to rust_bindgen
entry.content:
The bindgen target needs wrap_static_fns enabled and then the target

consuming the bindgen target needs a separate dependency. It would have

been cleaner if it generated a single mixed_shared_library, but the Rust

ecosystem has settled on a much more manual bindgen strategy, where the

bindgen output is include!ed into another crate. This means that we need

to export an action target with the file, making the generated

shared_library target separate.



Start using this in BoringSSL, which fills in a few missing bindings.

(bssl-crypto happens not to be using inline functions right now, which

is why it's working.)

entry.title: immersive fullscreen: allow overlay views to appear disabled
entry.content:
In immersive fullscreen LabelButton views in top chrome appear enabled

when the browser window is not active. This presents itself in the

following common scenarios:



* split screen chrome windows

* tab dragging

* space switching



The lack of LabelButton views visual updates on activation state leaves

the user without a clear visible indication of the change.



For compatibility with AppKit's fullscreen APIs the OverlayWidget does

not activate. Non activation is why hosted views do not update their

enabled state on browser activation changes.

entry.title: [A11y] Don't do any work when AXTreeCombiner combines only 1 tree
entry.content:
* tl;dr

This is a workaround in order to fix AXAssistantStructure, which

currently produces incorrect results for contenteditable values when AXTreeCombiner renumbers the nodes. It is also needed to unblock "stable ids" and per-tab auto disable accessibility.



* Description of bug

The value of a contenteditable node is the combined text of all

descendants, with newlines added for readability. AXAssistantStructure

currently produces incorrect results, because AXTreeCombiner renumbers

the tree, and when AXPosition looks up nodes by number, it gets the

wrong nodes.



The bug can already be seen in current results for the test

org.chromium.content.browser.accessibility.WebContentsAccessibilityTreeTest#test_ariaTextboxWithAriaTextboxChild. The current test expectations

are incorrect. If you look at the expected output file

(content/test/data/accessibility/aria/aria-textbox-with-aria-textbox-child-expected-android-assist-data.txt), the parent node should

have the same text property value as the child, "Baz".

Unfortunately, it uses another child "Bar" in its place (and the "Bar"

parent ends up using "Baz"). IOW, the parents have swapped children

for purposes of the contenteditable value computation.



* Cause of bug

The cause of this is that when AXPosition, which is used to aggregate

the descendant text, stores a node it uses an AXTreeID/AXNodeID pair.

However, in order to turn this into an AXNode, the AXTreeManagerMap is

used, but the AXTreeID being used is still points to the original tree

that was not renumbered.



* Workaround

This CL provides a workaround but does not fix the root problem.

The workaround is to fix the majority of cases (and those used in

tests), by having AXTreeCombiner be a noop in cases where there is

only one tree. Unfortunately, this means the bug would still exist

in a page with iframes.



* Long term fix

The long term way to fix this is to make AXPosition store weak pointers

to AXNodes, rather than AXTreeID/AXNodeID pairs. It also has

performance benefits. That has been

landed and reverted several times, because of issues with

text interfaces in UIA. See CL:5300830 for more information.



* Other possibilities

Another fix is to consider whether contenteditable values need to

aggregate the value of their descendants for use with snapshots or

AXTreeCombiner. Consumers of these APIs are unlikely to need the

text to be repeated, and in fact it would be a potential performance

fix as well.

entry.title: [accessibility] Ignore updates after web accessibility is disabled
entry.content:
When ui::AXMode::kWebContents is removed from a WebContents's

accessibility mode flags, each of its RenderFrameHostImpls resets their

connection with the RenderAccessibility interface in the renderer. It's

possible that a collection of updates and events could be in-flight to

the RenderAccessibilityHost or to the RenderFrameHostImpl. Such a

collection should be ignored, just as is the case if the collection's

reset token is out of date.



While there was logic for this in HandleAXEvents, it was checking that

the delegate's accessibility mode had all flags off. This condition is

not satisfied when native accessibility is still enabled. In this CL, we

switch from checking the delegate's mode flags to checking for a bound

connection to the renderer's RenderAccessibility. This avoids

duplicating the logic in UpdateAccessibilityMode, which unbinds the

connection when ui::AXMode::kWebContents is removed from the delegate's

mode flags.



This fixes one cause of ui::AXTree::RecordError failures along the lines

of "FATAL:ax_tree.cc ... 5 will not be in the tree and is not the new

root".

entry.title: [Default Nav Transition] Implement AnimationManager
entry.content:
Full impl of the AnimationManager interface for mainframe cross-doc

navigations only. Only the transformational animations are included

(i.e., layer moving animations). Does not include scrim or cross-fade

animations. Subframes, same-doc and cross-origin server redirects are

TODOs.



We use a new hook OnDidNavigate() to observe the finishing of a request

(committed successfully), and use DidFinishNavigation() to observe the

non-committed requests (204/205/Download, replaced or cancelled). Using

a new hook because the OnRenderWidgetHostViewSwapped() timing is too

late [1].



Edge cases:

- Another navigation commits while the user is still swiping across the

screen: synchronously destroy the impl_.

- Another navigation cancels our navigation and our navigation isn't

pending-commit. Play the cancel animation to bring back the active

page.

- Our navigation cancels other navigations. No action.

- With NavigationQueuing, a previously pending navigation has committed

before our navigation commits. No action.

- Our navigation has committed (so the animation manager is displaying

the invoke animation / waiting for the new renderer to submit a frame

/ displaying the cross-fade animation) while another navigation

commits. This can happen while navigation queuing or with a client

redirect. In this case we synchronously destroy the impl_.



[1]: OnRenderWidgetHostViewSwapped happens during

RFHManager::CommitPending, and CommitPending happens after

WCI::DidNavigateMainFramePreCommit [2]. At

DidNavigateMainFramePreCommit, we will reset the LocalSurfaceId on the

old View. Because we need to clone the old View's visual state, the

notification needs to be placed before the LocalSurfaceId is reset.

[2]: https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:content/browser/renderer_host/navigator.cc;drc=d3dcc876aec63f37b5c9b38281e7485ff24b7bd3;l=511

entry.title: Invalidation: Move token reading to other subscription reading
entry.content:
PerUserTopicSubscriptionManager::DropAllSavedSubscriptionsOnTokenChange

does multiple things. In particular, it reads the cached

instance_id_token to compare it with the new instance_id_token, which

was already stored in `instance_id_token_` outside of the function.



This is quite surprising as cached subscriptions are read during

Init() and the only call-site of the function knows the old and the

new token perfectly well, i.e. there's no need to read this from

cache every time.



This CL moves the reading of the registration token to the Init

function which also reads the other subscription data. This then

allows us to actually compare the old and new token without looking

at the cache.



This CL also clears any cached subscriptions in case of a cached

empty token. This could happen if we crashed in the middle of

DropAllSavedSubscriptionsOnTokenChange while clearing the token

because token and subscriptions are not written in a transaction.



Bug: b:325919924

entry.title: [//gpu] Init compositor thread DawnContextProvider only for Graphite
entry.content:
The compositor GPU thread currently always instantiates its

DawnContextProvider instance. However, this should be done only when

actually using Graphite (as GpuServiceImpl does). I currently noticed

this issue when experimenting with using Dawn's GL backend in Clank -

if I use Ganesh, configure WebGPU to use GL, and configure

DawnContextProvider to use Dawn's GL backend, errors result due to the

creation of the DawnContextProvider on the compositor GPU thread in

this case. I didn't track down the exact source of the errors at this

time, and it's possible that there is an issue here that will pop up

later for Graphite. If so, we'll see it once we get past the fundamental

issue of multithreading in Graphite's GLES backend. However, this is

clearly a correct change to make in any case.

entry.title: [ios] Fix session migration to allocate identifier in thread-safe way
entry.content:
It is possible for sessions to have CRWSessionStorage without a

valid WebStateID (the value is only saved since M-119, and this

has been found in production, see attached byg).



Since SessionIDGenerator is not thread-safe, the session migration

cannot call web::WebStateID::NewUnique() on the background thread

used to perform the migration on startup.



To fix this, change CRWSessionStorage -initWithCoder: to leave

-uniqueIdentifier unset of the value is missing (or invalid)

and change callers of ReadSessionWindow(...) to initialise the

field before use if invalid.



Change MigrateSessionsInPathsTo{Legacy,Optimized} to pass the next

identifier to use when loading the session, and to return back the

new value when the migration is complete (use this to update the

SessionIDGenerator after the migration).

entry.title: Add metrics to count how many fields are extracted by Autofill.
entry.content:
The motivation behind this addition is to measure the impact of

extending shadow DOM support to more cases.



The metric here is inevitably biased: We count forms and their fields

every time we extract a form. This means that for pages for which we

trigger form extraction more often, forms are counted more frequently.

Similarly, within a page, forms that the user interacts with are

extracted (and therefore counted) more frequently.

Nonetheless, given that other metrics (e.g. obtained by counting when

a form arrives in the browser), would be just as biased (albeit maybe

in different ways), we pick the simplest metric that we can record.

Should we require more detailed information, then we can refine it

in the future.
